comparative analysis of essential oil composition
using supercritical fluid extraction and solvent
The objective of this study was to compare the oil extraction yield and essential oil
L. extracted by using Supercritical Fluid Extraction
(SFE) and solvent extraction methods. In this study, a gas chromatography equipped with a mass
spectrophotometer detector was employed for qualitative analysis of the essential oil composi
L. The results indicated that the main fatty acid composition
identified in the essential oils extracted by using SFE and solvent extraction were linoleic acid
(22.4%–61.85%) and oleic acid (1.64%–18.97%). Thymoquinone (0.72%–21.03%) was found to
be the major volatile compound in the extracted
oil. It was observed that the oil extraction
efficiency obtained from SFE was significantly (
0.05) higher than that achieved by the solvent
extraction technique. The present study showed that SFE can be used as a more efficient technique
L. essential oil, which is composed of higher linoleic acid and thymo
quinone contents compared to the essential oil obtained by the solvent extraction technique.
